Review: Lightweight grief/romance dramedy, very much geared towards people who like Dan Levy (sure), Himesh Patel (so pretty) and Ruth Negga (all hail) and also have a fondness for bland rich people interior design (I’m not completely immune) and really nice cashmere knitwear (fucking love that). London, Paris, Margate. When my ludicrously gorgeous husband tragically dies, I pray he also leaves me a secret Parisian pied-à-terre and opulent sectional sofa.

Movie: Silver and the Book of Dreams

Review: So… I’m confused. Enhanced interrogation techniques: yeah or nah?

Googled the true story this is based on, and was astonished to find much of the dialogue is verbatim. Still, the main character’s recklessness and lack of professional oversight (this seems to be where the film most diverges from fact) feels transparently intended to inject a sense of peril. It does, though.

Movie: Mike Birbiglia: The Old Man and the Pool

Review: Corny, well-produced, competently executed, surprisingly watchable quasi-religious self-help cult propaganda. No one in this film has any sexual chemistry, yet the romantic waffle house-situated denouement feels genuinely poignant. And then… bang! Back to banality.
So bad I kinda liked it

Movie: How to Catch a Serial Killer

Review: I wouldn’t normally rate a movie I hadn’t watched to the end, but I’m 53 minutes in and life’s too short to spend a moment longer with these insufferable dipshits

Special call out to Michelle Forbes’s blunt Louise Brooks bob and general art goth vibe: truly aspirational.
